        "gradeId": "df44e923-d9be-4b5a-bd55-32364361c61e",
        "rubricName": "Pediatrics — PROF1: Professional Behavior",
        "content": "## PROF1: Professional Behavior — Level 3 / 5 · Competent\nPediatrics milestone · levels 1–5, novice → expert (Dreyfus)\n\n**Assigned level:** 3 · Competent — the highest level fully demonstrated; the ceiling here is set partly by limited opportunity to surface Levels 4–5 behaviors in a single, calm encounter.\n\n**Level progression:** Levels 1–3 demonstrated; Level 4 partially demonstrated; Level 5 not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity).\n\n## Evidence by level\n\n### Level 1 · Novice — Demonstrated\nThe learner displays expected professional behaviors: clear self-introduction, identifying role, and orienting to the patient's needs.\n\"Hi, Lauren. I am Dr. Rissman. I am the pediatrics resident taking care of Ava today. Um, and I hear you have questions, and I wanna see, um, what I can help most with today.\"\nThe learner also implicitly conveys the value of pediatrics as a vocation through the care taken to protect the infant and partner with the parent.\n\n### Level 2 · Advanced beginner — Demonstrated\nThe learner demonstrates professional behavior and accountability for patient care, committing to concrete follow-through.\n\"what we can do is I can write at the end of this, um, call, uh, the exact amount that we can give Ava to protect her from the fevers.\"\nProfessional behavior is sustained throughout with no lapses.\n\n### Level 3 · Competent — Demonstrated\nThe learner maintains professional behavior across an emotionally charged, vaccine-hesitancy conversation — a stressful and complex scenario where parental anxiety, online misinformation, and family pressure all converge. The learner stays patient, validating, and non-judgmental, and fully engages in the patient's care.\n\"my job is not to convince you one way or another, but just to show you the evidence.\"\n\"Thank you for sharing your worries and your hopes with me today.\"\nThe learner holds themselves accountable to the patient's understanding, pausing repeatedly to check comprehension: \"I just shared a lot, so I wanna pause and see, um, what questions you might have.\"\n\n### Level 4 · Proficient — Partially demonstrated\nLevel 4 turns on recognizing professionalism-lapse triggers and intervening to prevent lapses in self and others, plus exhibiting a sense of duty to patient care. The learner shows a clear sense of duty — staying with the parent's worries, declining to push, and securing follow-through on antipyretic dosing. However, the explicit recognition-and-intervention element (e.g., naming an emotionally loaded moment that could derail professional conduct and actively steering it) was only emerging; the learner remained composed but did not articulate a triggering risk in self or coach the family member (the aunt's advice) toward a better-grounded position. One notable honesty moment — \"I personally don't know the evidence that supports waiting four months\" — is professionally candid but reflects a knowledge limit rather than a deliberate lapse-prevention move.\n\n### Level 5 · Expert — Not assessable in this simulation (no opportunity)\nLevel 5 requires modeling professional behavior for and coaching others (e.g., peers/trainees) and extending the pediatrician's role into community, specialty, or profession-wide engagement. A single parent-counseling encounter with no learners, peers, or community context present gave no occasion for these behaviors to surface; this does not count against the learner.\n\n## Rationale\nThe learner met every Level 1–3 behavior. They introduced themselves and their role professionally, demonstrated accountability through concrete commitments to the patient's care, and — most importantly for Level 3 — maintained professional behavior throughout a genuinely complex and stressful counseling encounter. Faced with vaccine hesitancy fueled by online groups and family advice, the learner remained calm, validating, non-coercive, and fully engaged, repeatedly checking understanding and explicitly respecting the parent's autonomy (\"my job is not to convince you one way or another\"). This is the core of Competent professional behavior.\n\n## Why not the next level\nLevel 4 is defined by recognizing situations that may trigger professionalism lapses and intervening to prevent them in self and others, alongside a sense of duty. The learner showed a strong sense of duty but did not clearly demonstrate the lapse-recognition-and-intervention behavior — for instance, naming the frustration that misinformation can provoke and managing it deliberately, or coaching the family toward better information. The candid admission of not knowing the evidence for delaying, while honest, was a knowledge gap rather than a deliberate professionalism safeguard. These behaviors were only emerging, so the assignment holds at Level 3.\n\n## Recommendations\nTo target Level 4, name and manage the emotional triggers in such encounters and gently coach the family's influences. For example: \"When parents bring advice from family or online groups, I find it helps to address it directly without dismissing it — would it be okay if I gave you a few questions you could share with your aunt about where that advice comes from?\" This both prevents a defensive lapse and extends professional influence to others shaping the decision. Continuing the autonomy-respecting, non-judgmental stance already shown is exactly right.\n\n## Overall impression\n- **Strengths** — Maintained calm, validating, non-coercive professionalism throughout an emotionally charged vaccine-hesitancy conversation; respected parental autonomy explicitly; and followed through on concrete care commitments (antipyretic dosing). Repeatedly checked understanding rather than lecturing.\n- **Priority gaps** — Did not yet demonstrate the explicit recognition-and-intervention of professionalism triggers or coaching of others that distinguishes Level 4; one knowledge limitation (evidence on delaying schedules) surfaced. Level 5 behaviors had no opportunity to appear in this encounter.\n- **Top action items**\n  1. Practice naming and managing potential professionalism triggers (e.g., frustration with misinformation) aloud or in reflection, and steer them deliberately.\n  2. Offer the family practical tools to evaluate advice from relatives and online groups, extending professional influence beyond the patient in the room.\n  3. Strengthen the evidence base on vaccine scheduling so candor about knowledge limits can be paired with a confident, accurate answer.",
